        <!-- Task 3: Reading Passage 1 -->
        <div class="task-card" id="task3">
            <div class="task-header">
                <div class="task-title">📖 Task 3: IELTS Reading Passage</div>
                <div class="task-description">Answer Questions 1–13 based on the reading passage below.</div>
            </div>

            <div style="background: #f8f9fa; padding: 25px; border-radius: 10px; margin: 20px 0; line-height: 1.8;">
                <h2 style="color: #667eea; margin-bottom: 20px;">John Dewey: A Pioneer of Modern Education</h2>

                <p>John Dewey (1859–1952) was one of the most influential figures in the development of modern education. Born in the United States, he became widely known for his ideas about how students learn and the role of schools in society. Dewey believed that education should not simply involve the transfer of knowledge, but should instead encourage active thinking and real-world experience.</p>

                <p>Dewey grew up in a modest family and showed an early interest in philosophy and learning. After completing his university studies, he began working as a teacher. During this time, he became dissatisfied with traditional methods of instruction, which relied heavily on memorisation and repetition. He felt that such approaches did not prepare students for practical life.</p>

                <p>In the late nineteenth century, Dewey began to develop his own educational theories. He argued that students learn more effectively when they are actively involved in the learning process. Rather than listening passively to lectures, they should engage in problem-solving activities and collaborative tasks. This approach later became known as "learning by doing".</p>

                <p>Dewey also emphasised the importance of research in education. While working at the University of Chicago, he established a laboratory school where new teaching methods could be tested and evaluated. Teachers and researchers worked together to observe how students responded to different types of instruction. This allowed Dewey to refine his ideas based on evidence rather than assumption.</p>

                <p>One of Dewey's key contributions was his belief that education should reflect the needs of society. He argued that schools should prepare students to participate actively in a democratic community. This meant developing not only academic knowledge but also social skills such as cooperation and communication. His ideas influenced education systems both in the United States and internationally.</p>

                <p>Despite his success, Dewey's theories were not universally accepted. Some critics argued that his methods lacked structure and could lead to a decline in academic standards. Others believed that traditional approaches were more effective for certain subjects. Nevertheless, Dewey continued to promote his ideas through writing and public lectures.</p>

                <p>In addition to his work in schools, Dewey wrote extensively on philosophy and education. His books and articles were widely read and translated into many languages. As a result, his influence extended far beyond the United States, shaping educational practices in Europe and Asia.</p>

                <p>By the time of his death in 1952, Dewey had become a central figure in educational thought. Although some of his ideas have been modified over time, many of his principles remain relevant today. Modern approaches to teaching, particularly those that emphasise student engagement and critical thinking, continue to reflect his work.</p>
            </div>

